batrun (0.2.9-1) unstable; urgency=low

  * Suppress bogus standby projection when fewer than 5 suspend segments
    with measurable drain have been recorded; battery gauges with coarse
    resolution produce implausibly long estimates (e.g. 584 days) from
    just one or two short suspends. Output now shows how many more
    segments are needed instead.

 -- Jerko Čilaš <jerko@cilas.me>  Fri, 22 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000

batrun (0.2.8-1) unstable; urgency=low

  * Fix dpkg -i hanging after "Created symlink for batrun.service":
    the boot event no longer polls for gauge stabilisation (that poll
    is only needed after resume from sleep). dpkg starts the service
    synchronously, so the 300 s poll blocked the install.

 -- Jerko Čilaš <jerko@cilas.me>  Thu, 21 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000

batrun (0.2.7-1) unstable; urgency=low

  * Fix wildly inflated standby estimate caused by the ACPI battery
    driver returning a stale energy_now after long sleeps. The old poll
    exited at the first change from the pre-sleep value, recording only
    a fraction of the actual drain. The new poll waits until the gauge
    has been stable for 5 consecutive seconds (up to 300 s), giving the
    driver time to fully recalibrate regardless of sleep duration.

 -- Jerko Čilaš <jerko@cilas.me>  Wed, 21 May 2026 10:00:00 +0000

batrun (0.2.6-1) unstable; urgency=low

  * Run the post-wake recorder via `systemd-run --no-block` instead of
    `setsid ... &`. The previous detach kept the recorder in the
    systemd-sleep hook's cgroup, which systemd tore down on hook exit,
    killing the adaptive poll mid-run and losing the resume event.
    The transient unit gets its own cgroup and survives.

 -- Jerko Čilaš <jerko@cilas.me>  Wed, 20 May 2026 00:20:00 +0000

batrun (0.2.5-1) unstable; urgency=low

  * Detach the resume recorder from the systemd-sleep post hook so the
    adaptive post-wake battery poll no longer blocks the hook chain.
    Without this, the up-to-10s poll added in 0.2.4 stalled KDE /
    display-manager unlock by the same amount on every wake. The
    recorder still runs to completion in the background and writes the
    event whenever the battery driver yields a fresh reading.

 -- Jerko Čilaš <jerko@cilas.me>  Wed, 20 May 2026 00:05:00 +0000

batrun (0.2.4-1) unstable; urgency=low

  * Replace the fixed 2s post-wake delay with an adaptive loop: poll
    energy_now once per second up to 10s, exiting as soon as the
    reading changes. The 2s delay turned out to be too short on some
    laptops where the EC/driver keeps a stale value cached for longer.

 -- Jerko Čilaš <jerko@cilas.me>  Tue, 19 May 2026 23:55:00 +0000

batrun (0.2.3-1) unstable; urgency=low

  * On boot and resume events, wait 2s after the initial battery read
    and re-read /sys before inserting the event. Works around the
    kernel battery driver returning a stale energy_now right after
    wake, which made long auto-suspends look like zero drain.

 -- Jerko Čilaš <jerko@cilas.me>  Tue, 19 May 2026 21:45:00 +0000

batrun (0.2.2-1) unstable; urgency=low

  * Count structural segments separately from segments with measurable
    drain. Reports now show "N (M with measurable drain)" when the
    battery's reporting resolution swallows a segment's drain (typical
    for short suspends or short awake bursts). Average draw and runtime
    projections still derive only from measurable segments, so the
    headline numbers are unchanged -- the count is just honest.

 -- Jerko Čilaš <jerko@cilas.me>  Tue, 19 May 2026 21:30:00 +0000

